Victory of right-wing populists in Austria, totalling 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of the two parties of the so far Great Coalition and a significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties were brought, according to the first preliminary results, by the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖPP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer was seriously shaken, suffered a particularly strong loss.
On the other hand, the President of the Association for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the provincial magistrate of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing for a winning return to national politics.
Based on preliminary results, the country's strongest party will remain the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it lost 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which loses nearly nine percent of the vote by 25.6 percent.
These are the worst achievements of both major parties in Austria's post-war history so far, and especially in the People's Party that has brought about early elections, the result is literally disastrous.
In early July, upon leaving the ÖVP coalition, the People's Party had a significant advantage before the SPÖ according to polls.
However, the electorate apparently punished him for letting the government fail.
As early as the first reactions to the results, speculation has been expressed about the possible resignation of party president Wilhelm Molterer and current vice chancellor.
Observers believe that this could take place as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party presidency.
This development would probably facilitate the ever more likely way out of the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP Grand Coalition.
In view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Austrian Freedom Party (FPÖ) had previously obtained 18 percent of the votes and the BZÖ 11 percent of the votes - however, the Social Democrats expressed their fear of a repeat of the year 1999 when the People's Party agreed on joint governance with the populists (the FPÖ was united at the time, deposed from the BZÖ in 2005) which even caused sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and I assume he can return to Vienna for national politics, is obviously expecting this solution.
The Greens Party also reached parliament, which, however, lost somewhat of its popularity, and fell from third to fifth among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties exceeded the four-percent limit and did not make it to parliament.
