Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the fallen imperial endeavor.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the neo-renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms, with a tower each at the front corner, and looks like some kind of German country town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's going down a little bit.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious how large-scale an enterprise has had this westernmost gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "later future" of the conquests, intended to achieve its ambitions for occupying the Middle East through this railway from Damascus through Baghdad to what is now Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railway lines were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
Relative isolation from surrounding regions, caused by frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and displaced the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha Station was no better.
In 1917, an ammunition train exploded and destroyed the nicely crafted roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has slowly fallen to ruin, and history has gone well beyond.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to Anatolia and the entire Eastern region, it serves as an expanding diplomatic horizon for Turkey, at least in a symbolic sense.
The Justice and Development Party on the government - the AKP - has developed an entirely new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from surrounding regions, caused by frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, Iraq, Iran, and, of course, the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded the night train to Ankara, Turkish capital, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish Member of Parliament, Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of buzzing, which at the time also gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary film "The Night Mail" about the old world, I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the ottom.
However, the AKP, known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This created some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern building of stone and steel, specially designed for this purpose - standing in a developing suburban district, between semi-finished shopping centers and coffee houses. In the latter, middle managers in suits - both men and women - meet to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have fit a right-to-middle-oriented politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset order," he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
He had to turn east and west at the same time today.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open it both ways.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he'll be forced to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted a choice."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here almost mechanically repeated: Turkey's relations with not only the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea benefit Europe and the United States as well as Turkey itself.
It is as if they are trying to convey the message that, figuratively, together with Turkey, the whole of Europe can go to Asia and the Middle East on those eastbound railway lines.
When I was back at Hydarpasha Station, after another night, mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, the two German gentlemen who watched the recovery of this fancy structure 100 years ago.
How they would have wondered if they would have learned that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I was waiting at the port for the ferry to take me back through the Bosporus, it occurred to me that Turkey was once called "the sick man of Europe."
At least at the time, there was no question of which continent to claim this exciting country.
Memorable Ways of Life: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: Since 1962, as the musical director of Guildford, Vernon "Tod" Handley (an obituary, Sep 11) has led the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
Based on his musical plans for the part of town, he founded his wonderful youth choir Proteus the following year.
In principle, only those under the age of 21 could have belonged to the choir, but when Proteus sang their finale in 1979 - many of us were already in our late 20s - we simply refused to part with the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the name of the mythological shape changer) was in line with the choir's determination and ability to cope with any sheet music they put before it - whether it is madrigal or a Messiaen piece; without accompaniment, or with a large orchestral accompaniment.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing and always exciting, and it was thanks to the man whose inspiration we had for our enthusiasm for music remained unchanged over the years.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music speak on its own."
He always said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the sheet music.
So sing it!"
His conductorial technique was always completely understandable and accurate, but never dictatorial or exaggerating.
Whatever the level of music was, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote about him:
If there was ever an arm leader who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I was well acquainted with him during the two decades during which he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past forty years, I've written reviews of more than 100 concerts, but it's never, ever disappointed me, and it's often exhilarated me with them.
Tod Handley had greatness and modesty together, which is very rare.
He hated arm leaders who, in his words, simply "gallled with one or two well-known battlehorses throughout the world."
A lot of us are gonna miss it.
