The collision-avoiding "bee car"
For the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan this time drew inspiration from nature, precisely the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company designed a robot that avoids accidents by imitating bees' flyers.
An instrument called Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in developing impact prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center, in collaboration with the renowned Tokyo University's Advanced Research and Technology Research Centre, built this small robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Director of Technology PR and Research and Development Brands, defined BR23C as an additional extension of Nissan's four-tier security shell.
The robot improves the ability of the company's products to avoid collision.
During flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
However, more important is the role of the complex eye of the uterus, with which it can see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in each direction. Consequently, the uterus can fly undisturbed in its own personal space.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers designed a so-called laser telemeter (Laser Range Finder).
The instrument identifies obstacles within a range of up to 2 metres in a 180-degree field of vision before BR23C, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an action to avoid collision.
"As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot, mimicking the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a lower or greater angle to avoid collision.
The system is mostly distinguished from the instruments currently available by the fact that in this case the avoidance manoeuvre is carried out entirely automatically.
If not, the robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
In a manner other than bees, the bypass maneuver shall not be directed upwards or downwards, or diagonally, but shall only move in two dimensions and shall only move towards the rotation of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and manner, as is the case with bees.
Therefore, Nissan used a rotation function in addition to acceleration and slowing in the robot to avoid collisions.
"This device only has to process and react to data every few seconds.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can operate without interruption with just a few dozen KB memories.
This may sound surprising, but we're not even talking about memories the size of a gigabyte, but we're not even talking about memories the size of a megabyte.
This is the first step in developing immediate collision prevention technology that Nissan estimates can enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
The robot operates with lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could be an additional option to reach the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
