MUFG invests an additional $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities that provide it with a 10% return, and their exchange rate is $31.25.
According to Morgan Stanley, the global transaction is based on an average price of $29 which is 28% higher than the current exchange rate.
However, Morgan Stanley's share price dropped by 6.79% in Greenwich by around 17 p.m. and ended at $23.07.
"This strategic alliance offers Morgan Stanley a great opportunity to speed up its transformation into a banking company," explains John Mack, CEO of the U.S. Group.
Morgan Stanley approved the new status last week, by which it can diversify its activities, while at the same time under the control of the Federal Reserve.
The agreement with MUFG reaffirms that the current financial crisis demands even greater caution from corporate giants listed on Wall Street.
By the way, the terms announced on Monday show that the agreement has been amended in recent days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that it would sell 20% of its shares to the Japanese company for approximately $8.5 billion.
"A week ago we thought the stake would consist entirely of ordinary shares," explained Toshihide Mizuno, managing director of MUFG in Tokyo.
"However, due to the current market and economic situation, we wanted to minimize and prevent possible risks."
In terms of weighted average price, MUFG pays 7% more than book value for Morgan Stanley shares.
As a result of the transaction, the yield per share is reduced by about 20%.
Under the agreement, MUFG may convert half of its preference shares into ordinary shares after one year if the trading rate of the latter exceeds the exchange rate by more than 50% over a specified period, i.e. it rises to around $47.
Morgan Stanley thus ensures that it can make use of its investment opportunities, improve its balance sheet and increase its liquid resources using funds from MUFG.
However, the group's spokesperson did not want to give accurate information about the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following the association of MUFG, Morgan Stanley is expected to increase its Tier I solvency rate by about 15%, making it one of the best in its own sector.
Morgan said its balance sheet had improved "definitely" since the end of August.
The past few weeks have been a great ordeal for the group, as its stock price has fallen by half, while the cost of its insurance against default risk has skyrocketed.
This cost was reduced on Monday, but remained high, at around 12%.
Only one "survivor" of the large investor banks remained following the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, a Goldman Sachs that announced last week that he had made $15 billion: some of this came from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group of companies.
Rafael Correa's Monday statement, Quito
Rebuilding the Republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint plan for Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the pattern of fellow presidents and friends on Sunday, Correa explained her ideas about the new constitution.
He successfully completed his mission, as 64% of voters voted yes in the referendum according to official results, which concerned 80% of the vote.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the vote was invalid, while 0.7% were unfilled by voters.
The adoption of the draft constitution required 50% + 1 vote.
On Sunday, two surveys conducted at the exit of the polling offices and a census by a civil society organization both proved the vast superiority of the "yes" votes with a ratio of 63% and 70% respectively.
Rafael Correa, by the way, talked about the victory of his draft constitution as early as Sunday to Monday night.
"The Constitution has won an overwhelming victory," he stated, and thanked the Ecuadorians at his seat in Guayaquil, Governor, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report from the OAS surveillance mission, the vote was held in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text that summarized the principles of "new socialism" defended by the President.
The proposed constitution places state power in the service of the economy, maintaining the right of the state to "design development" for a country that essentially lives from oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign currency sent by emigrators.
The draft Constitution of Correa, elected in 2006, also confirms the power of the head of state, who can obtain seats for up to two consecutive periods and is entitled to dissolve the Parliament.
Correa has already announced that she intends to take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again for the head of state mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also included the freeness of health services and education. The President had already started to introduce it in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants, and half the population lives below the subsistence minimum.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could end Quito and Washington's agreement to use the Ecuadorian facility as a basis for US anti-drug measures.
They freed 19 hostages in Chad.
Egyptian commando ambushed the kidnappers who took eleven tourists and their eight escorts hostage ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts were detained in the desert for ten days, from which they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were released in Chad during the morning by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in good condition, they arrived by plane at al-Maza military base at around 2:30 p.m., which is directly connected to Cairo International Airport.
The hostages were forbidden to make a statement to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, Cairo's suburban residential area, where they were examined.
The hostages are "healthy" and the kidnappers were "not paid a ransom," said Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna at the airport.
The hostages were captured on 19 September at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border regions of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they participated in an SUV safari. The group was then carried from one hiding place to another by the 35 unknown hostage takers.
The group had 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman), as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard and director of the safari organizer Aegyptous travel agency.
According to an Egyptian security chief, a 30-member special commando arrived on two helicopters at the scene where the hostage takers were ambushed just before dawn.
"There was a firefight between the troops. Half the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," claimed the leader who requested his name to be silenced.
He also said that a total of 150 special forces were sent from the Lightning Brigade in Egypt to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos were added.
Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, just in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian action groups.
"We must acknowledge that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our secret service people and action groups," he stated, without further details.
He also denied that the hostages were being ransomed.
The day before, the Sudanese army announced that an SUV had been intercepted while patrolling, six of them (including the Chadian leader) were killed, and two were arrested.
The army claimed that the hostage takers were associated with a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which was immediately refuted by the organization concerned.
