Part of Fortis bank is nationalised by Benelux governments
With partial nationalisation, the Benelux states help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, the first European, due to the spillover effect of the US credit market crisis: the three countries will support the financial and insurance institution, which also has interests in Hungary, with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and the Dutch governments agreed on the case at the highest level at the end of the week, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Competition Officer.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank is the first major crisis in the context of the international financial market crisis that has been rolling in waves for more than a year, and decisions on the bank can therefore be considered a precedent in some ways.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, all three states acquire nearly half (49 percent) of the bank's existing property there.
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, including, above all, the activities purchased from ABN Amro in the Netherlands last year, mainly as insurance companies.
Fortis' shares began to plummet last week, with serious crisis phenomena at the institute in the second half of the week.
Analysts agree, however, that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too large to be allowed to go bankrupt.
The company's papers only dropped by about 12 percent on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the stock value has decreased by more than two thirds.
In terms of current share prices, the total market capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but corporate directors say this is not realistic.
The company management also blamed overseas market uncertainties over the adoption of the US $700 billion package plan for the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers had already risen slightly.
On Friday, a new CEO was appointed to head the bank in the person of Filip Dierckx.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but no one has reported with a substantial offer.
The Belgian Government has already indicated that investors do not have to worry or lose money.
There has been no panic among the bank's clients so far, the accounts have not been stormed.
In Hungary Fortis has an independent branch and acquired leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign insurance contracts with the candidate based on people's drug purchase data.
Data protection professionals fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned in each case.
This must be in independent hands, otherwise we leave the henhouse to the fox," quoted Richard Dick, the developer of the program for tracking prescriptions, in the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in case of damage events dependent on the health condition of the applicant client, and if they consider the risk too high, they do not even make insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the light of the results of the investigation.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: he easily obtains from pharmacies, based on the customer's identification number, what drugs he has purchased in the last year and a half, and the program itself concludes what disease he is suffering from and what his health status is.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol lowering, it suggests that you have virtually unmanageable levels of fat in your blood, which immediately classifies you as a higher risk.
Several versions of the programme are in circulation, some of them also determine a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do besides paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
Disadvantages include that some medicines may be used for multiple purposes, such as some compounds may be used to treat migraines or hot flushes, but they may also be effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-enhancing factor for business insurers and not the former.
To retrieve and process the data, separate companies have formed, and they ask for the patient's consent before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
They are now bound by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure to do so.
Some companies are now processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data, so they can provide a more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and it will be increasingly difficult to control the use at the same time.
There is a separate health data protection law, but it covers only healthcare providers and insurance companies.
Congress has a bill that also gives authorities control over businesses specialising in reporting.
Dick Richard admits that this is not enough: he therefore improved his program, which would link the transmission of the data to the explicit consent of the data subject.
Another question is that the person concerned can hardly refuse consent, otherwise the insurers will not sign a contract with him.
Thus, the hens are somewhat dependent on the benevolence of the fox.
