Doubles trade between the European Union and India
Since the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, the agenda of the ninth summit has been dominated by this topic, alongside other, largely global problems.
Today there will also be a French-Indian summit, where we will be talking mainly about nuclear cooperation.
The European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic power that should be given greater say in international affairs, but that the Member States have not yet been able to reach common ground on whether to support New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This issue was thus not called into question at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as EU President-in-Office, and Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double in five years, i.e. increase trade turnover to a hundred billion euros.
Given the fact that trade in goods between 2000 and 2007 has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not a very ambitious target.
In this context, in legal terms, the twenty-six bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been consolidated, i.e. air traffic may also soar in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiation.
The aim is to balance out that while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth in the EU's partner list.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, as well as terrorism, has been condemned on both sides in all its forms and has called for the UN conference to be convened.
They also called for the completion of the Doha trade round, although both of them have a large share in the failure so far.
The EU has confirmed its commitment to its energy and climate programme, i.e. to reduce emissions by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed with this, as well as that a global deal should be made at the climate conference to come next year and that greenhouse gas production should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
I would also like to hinder the rise in food prices and support the call for an international meeting to review the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is going to the French capital today, where he is preparing to make a deal at the bilateral meeting on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
In Paris, they are confident that French companies will be commissioned to build nuclear reactors in India with a value of €20 billion.
