More than three hundred Italian publishing houses in Frankfurt
Italian publishers are represented with a strong field at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than three hundred Italian publishing houses will be present at the most important international copyright meeting, the 60th Buchmesse Fair.
For this year's Frankfurt International Book Fair, 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries are expected in 171.790 square meters, where more than 403,000 books will be presented.
At the opening ceremony of the Italian Pavilion, the Italian government will be represented by Francesco Maria Giro, Deputy State Secretary of the Ministry of Cultural Goods and Activities: Italy will occupy a 264 square metres exhibition area through the establishment of a unified Italia Point.
The opening ceremony will be followed by a press conference in the "Room Struktur" room of the Buchmesse 5.0 pavilion, where there will also be an opportunity to present information, trends and prospects on the situation of Italian publishing.
According to the data, the proportion of foreign authors on the Italian publishing market is constantly declining, especially in the field of adult and youth publications.
They found the missing billionaire Steve Fossett's plane a year ago.
They found the remains of the billionaire Steve Fossett's plane, who disappeared over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-metre high plateau in the area of Mammoth Lakes in the Sierra Nevada Mountains on the border between California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the aircraft.
John Anderson, the Sheriff of Madera County, dispelled all remaining doubts: "After establishing the plane's position, we sent out a team, and now we can be sure it's about the plane that Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff further confirmed that no human remains were found in the plane or surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Transport Safety Bureau (NTSB) said that a commission of inquiry was asked a few hours after the discovery of the wreck, which managed to identify the plane and to establish that it really was the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett left Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday also in California, not far from the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal belongings near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two I.D.s in Fosset's name issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire set up a number of peaks through which he enrolled himself in history.
In 2002, on the sixth attempt, he first managed to fly around the earth with a balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he also bypassed the ground by plane, without landing.
Many of his records also include flying over the Andes, at an altitude of 15.445 metres, which he performed with a co-pilot.
